\headerbox{Genetics}{name=genetics,span=2,column=1,row=0}{
\textbf{Methods:} Genomic DNA extracted via CTAB method %cite{ctab}
, large sub-unit (LSU) ribosomal DNA (rDNA) region D8-D10 (799 bp) and the small-sub unit (SSU) rDNA (1699) regions were amplified via PCR. Sanger sequencing was conducted by Macrogen (Korea). Sequences (D8-D10 rDNA 799 bp, SSU rDNA 1699 bp) were aligned with \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp. sequences from GenBank via MUSCLE (8 iterations). Phylogenetics were calculated with Bayesian inference (BI, MrBayes 3.2.2, 2,000,000 generations subsampled every 1000th) as well as maximum likelyhood (ML, PhyML, 1000 bootstraps) using Geneious v8. \\
\textbf{Results:} 
\begin{center}
	\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{phylo-sml.jpg}
	%\includegraphics[width=0.49\linewidth]{D8D10.jpg}
\end{center}
}

\headerbox{Thecal plate structure}
{name=morphology,span=2,column=1,below=genetics}{
\textbf{Methods:} Type strain HG7 was preserved with 10\% Lugol's iodide then analysed by \\
(1) Flourescent Brightner 28 (Sigma, St Louis, USA) addition under UV (Olympus BX51 microscope, Olympus DP73 camera).\\
(2) scanning electron microscopy (Tescan Vega3 microscope, 15kV) at the Senckenberg amd Meer.\\
\textbf{Results:} 


	\includegraphics[width=0.7\linewidth]{morph.jpg}
	%\includegraphics[width=0.49\linewidth]{CPA_3d_cumulative}

}

\headerbox{Size}{name=size,span=2,column=1,row=0,below=morphology}{
\textbf{Methods:} Strains HG4, HG6 HG7 and HG26 were fixed in 10\% Lugol's iodide during exponential growth phase and examined with inverted light microscope (Nikon Eclipse TS100, Infinite Luminera 1 camera). Depth (along dorso-ventral axis) and width (along lateral axis) were meassured for 30 to 36 cells per strain (n=128). \\
\textbf{Results:} 
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.5\linewidth]{graph.jpg}
\end{center}
}

\headerbox{Conclusion}{name=conc,span=2,column=1,row=0,below=size}{
Evidence for for \emph{Gambierdiscus lapillus} sp. nov. due to genetic distinction from other \emph{Gambierdiscus} spp., coupled with morphology and diminutive siz. The species is named for the latter along with heavy plate ornamentation characteristic of it's members. Latin, lapillus (= little gem).
}

